# Koren Android Project Rules

This document outlines key coding conventions and architectural patterns used in the Koren Android project.

## General Principles

-   Adhere strictly to existing patterns found in the codebase.
-   Before adding new code (classes, functions, modules), **review similar existing code**.
-   Avoid obvious comments; only comment non-trivial logic. No inline comments.

## Module Structure & Dependencies

-   **Feature modules should NOT depend directly on other feature modules.**
-   Inter-feature navigation is handled via lambda callbacks passed from the central NavHost (in `:app`) into feature Screen composables.
-   Repository interfaces and implementations belong in `core/data/src/main/java/com/koren/data/repository/`.
-   Use Cases belong in `core/domain/src/main/java/com/koren/domain/`.
-   Common data models belong in `core/common/src/main/java/com/koren/common/models/`.
-   Feature UI code (Screens, ViewModels, States, Components) resides in `feature/{feature_name}/src/main/java/com/koren/{feature_name}/ui/`.
-   Feature navigation definitions (destinations, NavGraphBuilder extensions) reside in `feature/{feature_name}/src/main/java/com/koren/{feature_name}/navigation/`.

## Data Models (`:core:common`)

-   Models should be plain, immutable Kotlin data classes.
-   Avoid framework-specific dependencies (e.g., Firebase `ServerValue`) directly in common models. Handle such logic in the Repository layer (`:core:data`).
-   Do not add empty constructors or helper functions unless necessary and standard practice elsewhere.

## ViewModel Implementation (using `StateViewModel`)

-   Extend `com.koren.common.util.StateViewModel<Event, State, SideEffect>`.
-   Use `@HiltViewModel` and `@Inject`.
-   Use **Molecule** for state management within the `init` block:
    ```kotlin
    private val scope = CoroutineScope(viewModelScope.coroutineContext + AndroidUiDispatcher.Main)
    init {
        scope.launchMolecule(mode = RecompositionMode.ContextClock) {
            val data1 by flow1.collectAsState(...)
            val data2 by flow2.collectAsState(...)
            // Logic to update _uiState based on collected data
             when (val currentState = uiState.collectAsState().value) {
                is SpecificUiState.Success -> {
                    _uiState.update { currentState.copy(...) }
                }
                else -> { // Handle Loading, Error, etc. -> transition to Success
                     _uiState.update { SpecificUiState.Success(...) }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    ```
-   Collect flows using `collectAsState(...)` inside `launchMolecule`.
-   Update state using `_uiState.update { ... }`.
-   Handle events using `override fun handleEvent` and `withEventfulState<StateType>`.
-   Emit side effects via `_sideEffects.emitSuspended(...)`.
-   Run repository calls or other suspending operations in `viewModelScope.launch(Dispatchers.IO)`.

## UI State / Event / SideEffect Definitions

-   Define as sealed interfaces (`{ScreenName}UiState`, `{ScreenName}Event`, `{ScreenName}SideEffect`) typically in `{ScreenName}UiState.kt`.
-   The primary success/shown state (e.g., `Success`, `Shown`) should implement `EventHandler<Event>`.

## Compose UI Conventions

-   Structure screens as: `{ScreenName}` -> `{ScreenName}Content` -> (Optional) `{ScreenName}SpecificStateContent`.
-   `{ScreenName}` composable: Main entry point, collects state (`collectAsStateWithLifecycle`), handles side effects (`CollectSideEffects`), sets scaffold state (`LocalScaffoldStateProvider`), calls `{ScreenName}Content`.
-   `{ScreenName}Content` composable: Contains the main `when(uiState)` block, delegating rendering to state-specific composables. Does not contain complex layout logic itself (e.g., no `Box` wrapper if state composables provide their own).
-   Create dedicated, private composables for each distinct UI state (e.g., `Loading`, `Error`, `Success`, `NoFamily`). These handle their own layout (e.g., contain the `Box` for centering).
-   Screens should **NOT** define their own `Scaffold`.
-   Use `LocalScaffoldStateProvider.current.setScaffoldState(...)` **directly** within the main screen composable body (not inside `LaunchedEffect`) to control the central scaffold's appearance (title, bars).
-   Handle side effects using the `CollectSideEffects` composable. Suspend functions (like `onShowSnackbar`) can be called directly within its lambda (no extra `CoroutineScope` needed).
-   In custom composables, the `modifier: Modifier = Modifier` parameter should be the **first** optional parameter.
-   Avoid passing modifiers down unnecessarily if a child composable handles its own layout/sizing (e.g., dedicated state composables filling the screen).
-   In `when` statements, **omit curly braces `{}`** for branches calling a single function/composable.
-   Provide `@ThemePreview` composables for content/state-specific UI parts.

## Navigation

-   Use `kotlinx.serialization` (`@Serializable object` or `data class`) for navigation destinations.
-   Define NavGraphBuilder extension functions (e.g., `chatScreen(...)`) in the feature's `navigation` package.
-   Pass necessary parameters (`NavController`, `onShowSnackbar`, navigation lambdas) into these extension functions.
-   Call these extensions from the central `NavHost` in the `:app` module (`app/src/main/java/com/koren/navigation/KorenNavHost.kt`). 